Thanks for the request! You're correct that `SKGLView.Dispose()` is currently non-virtual, which prevents subclasses from properly overriding disposal. The same limitation exists in `SKCanvasView`.

The standard .NET solution would be to adopt the `Dispose(bool disposing)` pattern:

```csharp
public void Dispose()
{
    Dispose(true);
    GC.SuppressFinalize(this);
}

protected virtual void Dispose(bool disposing)
{
    if (disposing)
    {
        dpiWatcher.Unsubscribe(OnDpiChanged);
        sizeWatcher.Dispose();
        interop.Dispose();
    }
}
```

As a workaround in the meantime, you can use a wrapper/composition approach rather than subclassing, implementing `IDisposable` in your wrapper class and disposing the view from there.
